1.2.4 Fitting the Training Data and Hypertuning the model using Grid Search¶

In [18]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

param_grid = {'C': [0.1, 1, 10, 100]}
class_weights = {0:0.1,1:0.9}

log_reg = LogisticRegression(penalty='l1', solver='liblinear',class_weight=class_weights)

grid_search = GridSearchCV(log_reg, param_grid, cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_train_annual_scaled, y_train_annual)

best_params = grid_search.best_params_
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_

y_pred = best_model.predict(X_test_annual_scaled)

print("The best hyperparameters for the model is:",best_params)
best_model

coefficients = best_model.coef_[0]

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

# Define the parameter grid for Decision Tree (for GridSearchCV)

              'min_samples_split': [2, 4, 6, 8],
              'min_samples_leaf': [3, 4, 8]}

# Define the parameter grid for Decision Tree (for GridSearchCV)
param_grid = {'max_depth': [10,12,14,16,18, 20],
              'min_samples_split': [2, 4, 6, 8],
              'min_samples_leaf': [3, 4, 8]}
class_weights = {0:0.1,1:0.9}

# Create a Decision Tree classifier
decision_tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight=class_weights,random_state=1147)

# ------------------------------------ GRID SEARCH ---------------------------------------------------------#
# Initialize GridSearchCV
grid_search_tree = GridSearchCV(decision_tree, param_grid, cv=5)

# Fit the model to the training data
grid_search_tree.fit(X_train_monthly, y_train_monthly)

# Get the best hyperparameters and the best model
best_params_tree_grid = grid_search_tree.best_params_
best_model_tree_grid = grid_search_tree.best_estimator_

# Print the best hyperparameters for GridSearchCV
print("The best hyperparameters for the Decision Tree model using GridSearchCV are:", best_params_tree_grid)

param_dist = {'max_depth': scipy.stats.randint(5, 31),

              'min_samples_leaf': scipy.stats.randint(1, 11)}

# Initialize RandomizedSearchCV
random_search_tree = RandomizedSearchCV(decision_tree, param_distributions=param_dist, n_iter=10, cv=5, random_state=42)

# Get the best hyperparameters and the best model for RandomizedSearchCV

Conclusion¶

Annual Features (best dataset)

Logistic regression (Best Model)¶

After evaluating three machine learning algorithms for a binary classification problem, I found that the best model for this particular dataset was Logistic Regression with assigned class weights. The model was assessed using various metrics, including accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and the ROC curve (AUC).

Our most important key performance indicator in this case is recall, aiming to minimize false negatives since we want a model accurately predicting customer churn.

Decision Trees outperformed Random Forest in terms of accuracy (same as Logistic Regression). It correctly predicted positive responses, outperforming the other models. While Random Forest predicted a large number of positive responses, the model struggled without oversampling due to imbalanced data, leading to no prediction of positive responses (no True Positives). Hence, Random Forest didn't perform well in predicting TPs and minimizing FNs. Logistic Regression was able to predict a few TPs with better precision.

The Logistic Regression model was precise in predicting both negative and positive responses, with a precision score of 0.235, the highest among the three algorithms.

Recall, focusing on the number of false negatives, was also high in Decision Tree without oversampling, with a value of 0.617.

The F1-score, combining precision and recall, was highest in Logistic Regression, indicating the model's ability to classify observations correctly.

Analyzing the ROC curve, the Log-Regression model performed well, with an AUC of 0.76 in the test case, indicating effective distinction between positive and negative observations.

Overall, Logistic Regression was the best model, providing the highest accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and area under the ROC curve.

When comparing annual features versus monthly features, Random Forest and Decision Tree models performed comparatively better on annual features. Feature importance also highlighted the sum of transactions in 12 months as a significant feature, suggesting that monthly features capturing short-term trends may be less impactful. Annual trends may offer a better measure for creating a predictive model to confirm if a customer might respond positively to a campaign.

Among all models, for the chosen hyperparameter space, Logistic Regression performs well on annual features, better than Random Forest and Decision Trees. While oversampling is an option, the primary concern is the bias it introduces. Creating artificial data may help model the current data but may not be impactful for future predictions.
